ocultural landscapes of the United States, pre- and post-9/11. From her Canadian perspective, Relke focuses on Star Trek's uniquely American version of liberal humanism, extends it into a broader analysis of ideological features, and avoids a completely positive or negative critique, choosing instead to honour the contradictions inherent in the complexity of the subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanismxHistoryy20th century. 0aStar Trek television programsxPhilosophy. 0aStar Trek television programsxPolitical aspects. 0aStar Trek television programsxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aAmerican liberal humanism.  abooks about star trek.  acultural studies.  aexploring star trek.  agender and star trek.  ahumanism.  amedia studies.  apop culture studies.  aposthumanism.  asci-fi.  ascience fiction studies.  ascience fiction.  astar trek at university.  astar trek course.  astar trek cultural studies.  astar trek science.  astar trek studies.  astar trek.  atelevision studies.  atv studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552383308?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552383308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552383308/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles